<HEAD>Study Says Most Companies Do Little To Promote Voting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The promotion of voting is not among the priorities of many of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s companies even though the nation is facing a voter participation `` crisis,'' a private group says. People for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that 60 percent of the Fortune 500 companies surveyed conduct little or no organized non-partisan voter registration, education or get-out-the-vote activities. And only 6 percent have voter participation activities that reach beyond their own employees, the group said. Ninety-one of the Fortune 500's top 100 corporations responded to the group's phone and mail surveys, which were conducted in April and May. <PERSON> Melanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Verveer </PERSON>, vice president of the group, said the nation is facing the `` grim possibility'' that for the first time in its history, less than half of the eligible voters will be going to the polls in the presidential election. `` This crisis in participation is the result of a three-decade-long slide in voter participation that threatens to turn our government by all the people into government by less than half the people,'' Ms. <PERSON> Verveer </PERSON> said. She said new institutions must take the lead to stem declining voter participation and she noted that a few businesses have taken exciting initiatives. <PERSON> Sherrod </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, said many major corporations in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> have printed up voter registration forms and mailed them to customers as part of their monthly billing procedures. `` We figure we will put literally millions of registration forms, without government spending ... into prospective voters' hands,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>, vice president of the Cleveland-based <ORGANIZATION> Ameritrust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said his company began offering voter registration services in <LOCATION> Cuyahoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> to its customers and the general public in 1982. `` As a result of our success and the fact that we've had such a good response ... we're going to take this program to the 11 other counties in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> where we have branches,'' <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Verveer </PERSON> said that `` the inescapable conclusion of our study is that for the majority of corporations, voter registration is nowhere to be found on their list of priorities.'' The Washington-based People for the American Way is a non-partisan constitutional liberties organization that conducts public education programs on constitutional issues.
</TEXT>
