<HEAD>Uprising, Labor Disputes Heat Up Inflation, Slow Growth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Palestinian uprising, election year politics and protracted labor disputes are undermining <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s economic recovery program by pushing up inflation and reducing growth Industrial production is down 3.5 percent, the first such drop in eight years, and inflation is expected to exceed 20 percent, up from 16 percent last year and a third higher than initially forecast. `` We had to scale down our expectations'' after more optimistic projections in early 1988, said <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowental </PERSON>, assistant director general of economic affairs in the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The gloomier prognosis is accompanied by a `` feeling of insecurity because nobody knows what's going to happen after the -LRB- Nov. 1 national -RRB- election,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Canaan </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> journalist who writes for two West German economic publications. A key reason for the slump is the 8-month-old Arab uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> already has eaten up more than half of this year's growth, initially projected at 3.7 percent. The uprising has cost more than $ 700 million in lost tourism, uncollected taxes and additional military expenses, said <PERSON> Amnon </PERSON> <PERSON> Neubach </PERSON>, an economic adviser to Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>. In addition, fewer of the 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied lands buy <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> products and about 20 percent of the 110,000 Palestinians working in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> no longer report to their jobs as a result of a Palestinian boycott. `` When you have 1.5 million consumers who used to buy Israeli products, and they stopped doing it, it has a serious effect,'' said an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> industrialist, speaking on condition of anonymity. Stability is also threatened by increasing wage demands, backed by numerous strikes by Israeli workers. Excluding Palestinian work stoppages, the Israeli economy lost 1.3 million work days due to strikes in 1987, more than triple the 1986 figure. The labor disputes indicate workers are no longer willing to make the kind of sacrifices they accepted during a 1985 austerity program. Workers then accepted wage cuts of up to 20 percent to help stem soaring inflation and reduce a $ 3 billion budget deficit. The program worked. Inflation dropped to 16.1 percent in 1987, and the budget deficit fell from 13.6 percent of the Gross Domestic Product of 1.2 billion shekels in 1984 to a surplus of 1.7 percent of the 1986 GDP of 1.3 billion shekels -LRB- $ 812 million -RRB-. But in the past two years, real wages have been rising faster than productivity, heating up inflation. And Finance Minister <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nissim </PERSON> is under growing pressure to make concessions as the election campaign is heating up. `` Our basic target is to maintain stability,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lowental </PERSON> said. `` But nobody knows what's going to happen with the wages.'' Still unsigned is a tentative agreement for an 11 percent wage increase over two years for the 450,000 civil servants, one-third of the civilian labor force. Also unresolved are private sector negotzed national health system with months of strikes and slowdowns. The government agreed to emergency payments to ease the backlog of 15,000 Israelis waiting for operations, but there has been little progress in wage talks for doctors who earn an average $ 700 a month and are seeking wage hikes of more than 20 percent. If the doctors get large increases, `` it could affect the whole wage structure. If you give higher wages to one group of people, you have to give more to all the others,'' said <LOCATION> Canaan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nissim </PERSON> also is under pressure to devalue the Israeli shekel which has been fixed at a rate of about 1.6 shekels to the dollar since the days of hyperinflation. Manufacturers complain the strong shekel is making it difficult for Israeli exports to compete and is partly to blame for the drop in industrial production. <PERSON> Nissim </PERSON> has refused to devalue for fear of raising import prices and fueling inflation. Especially hard hit is <ORGANIZATION> Koor </ORGANIZATION>, the industrial conglomerate of the powerful <ORGANIZATION> Histadrut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, which lost $ 250 million in 1987, a record in Israeli industry. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which gives <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> $ 1.2 billion a year in economic aid, urged <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to sell off state-owned companies, lower taxes and cut government spending. The government has taken some steps in that direction. But <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Barkai </PERSON>, economics professor at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said no unpopular steps would be taken during the three-month election campaign. `` The government must close down unprofitable factories and cut spending. But there wo n't be any changes in economic policy before the elections,'' <PERSON> Barkai </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
