members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> guarantee the truce and other elements of a peace plan. The five _ <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ are considering the issue, the sources said. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> did not spell out his proposals for reporters and said he has not yet received a formal response from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Diplomatic sources say <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> is not enthusiastic about the idea, but stopped short of outright rejection of the proposed simultaneous announcement. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s response, although not formal, has been `` constructive.'' `` Unfortunately, from the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> side, I have not received the comments which I have asked for,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> told reporters as he left <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. Meanwhile, the official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said in a dispatch from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>, who heads <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s negotiating team, met Thursday with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>, Ambassador <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, and visiting Indian Foreign Minister P.V. <PERSON> Narasimha </PERSON> <PERSON> Rao </PERSON>. The agency said the men discussed the cease-fire resolution and other issues, but gave no other details. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said that next week, probably Wednesday, he would deliver a comprehensive report to the council on the cease-fire declaration, troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange and other elements of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peace plan. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have waged war since 1980, when <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded Iranian territory. The death toll is estimated at 1 million. The <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in July 1987 adopted a resolution calling for a cease-fire in the war, which has prompted an escalated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval presence in the gulf. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> accepted the proposal, but it was not until last month that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, after a series of battlefield defeats, said it, too, would accept the resolution. Since then, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has launched several attacks on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to bolster its bargaining position. Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> met the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief for more than one hour Thursday. The Iranian envoy made no comments as he left the meeting. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> says it needs the direct talks as a guarantee of sincerity from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which it fears will seek only a temporary truce to regroup forces.
