<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearVerification     08-05 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Verification,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Prepare for Monitoring Experiment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists and construction workers swarmed over this scenic, sunbaked plateau Thursday, making final preparations for an historic U.S.-Soviet nuclear weapons verification experiment later this month. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said the Aug. 17th test and another planned in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> next month were a `` breakthrough in negotiations between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on nuclear testing. `` It is unprecedented to be able to exchange this type of data,' said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, the chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator at talks with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on nuclear testing. Reporters were taken Thursday to the test site 130 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> for a day-long briefing and an impromptu news conference held on a platform four-tenths of a mile above the nuclear device. The blast will have an explosive punch of up to 150 kilotons, nearly 12 times the force of the atomic bomb that destroyed the Japanese city of <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> 43 years ago Saturday. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Behne </PERSON>, test director from <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, told the gathering that no one would be allowed within 15 miles of the site when the device is detonated. The experiment is designed to test the ability of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to monitor the size of each other's nuclear tests Such monitoring is critical to comply with treaties limiting the size of nuclear tests under a policy of `` trust but verify.'' Treaties limiting tests to no more than 150 kilotons were passed in 1974 and 1976 but never ratified. Some three dozen Soviet scientists will be on the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> test site for this month's blast, code-named <PERSON> Kearsarge </PERSON>. American scientists will monitor the September Soviet test at <LOCATION> Semipalatinsk </LOCATION>. The device that will be detonated later this month was delivered July 20 and placed 180 feet above the bottom of a 2,200-foot vertical shaft. The Soviet scientists, who have been on the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> site since spring, were not allowed to see the device itself, according to <PERSON> Behne </PERSON>. But the Soviets were allowed to examine the 8-foot canister holding the device once the container, painted red white and blue, was sealed. The joint verification experiment will focus on cables half an inch in diameter, running to the site of detonation from instrument trailers hundreds of yards away and down to the device itself. Additional cables are placed in a second hole 30 feet away from and parallel to the weapon shaft. The tests come two years after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed using a system called Corrtex, which is designed to measure the size of a nuclear blast by the shock waves emitted from the nuclear device. The Soviets will be using a similar system of their own called <PERSON> Miz </PERSON> and a second system which takes similar measurements. The joint tests are to determine whether the two monitoring systems are compatible and whether explosions can be monitored by having the cables only in the second hole. The sticking point for both countries has been the idea of allowing one country to place monitoring cables in the same hole as the device itself. The breakthrough on the test verification issue came late last year in talks at <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> when both sides agreed to exchange scientists and monitor a test at each site. Officials say that if the monitoring systems work, each country could have scientists at the other's nuclear test site for all future tests.
</TEXT>
