<HEAD>Minor Tax Changes Would Help Various Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS one graf after 5th graf bgng ``The chief ... '' to
explain changes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Thursday gave lopsided bipartisan approval to a $ 7.1 billion election-year package of minor tax changes that would benefit farmers, mutual-fund owners, free-lance writers and rural mail carriers. The targeted tax cuts would be financed by higher taxes on defense contractors, certain other corporations, pipe smokers and purchasers of single-premium life insurance policies. The 380-25 vote for the bill was easily the widest margin by which any tax legislation has been approved over the last decade. Voting for the measure were 230 Democrats and 150 Republicans; 6 Democrats and 19 Republicans voted no. The bill now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has approved a stripped-down version. The chief purpose of the 960-page <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill is to correct errors and clear up ambiguities in the landmark tax overhaul enaced in 1986. Since this is almost certainly the only tax bill with a chance of becoming law this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> used it to carry dozens of substantive tax changes. Despite its size, the bill is one of the smallest pieces of tax legislation in recent years. The <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> estimates it would cut taxes by about $ 7.1 billion through 1991 and raise taxes by about $ 47 million less than that amount. Nevertheless, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., committee chairman, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, `` This bill is in keeping with the spirit of tax reform. He and Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Archer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, senior Republican on the committee, emphasized that unlike most tax bills of recent years, the legislation includes no tax breaks that are targeted for the benefit of only one or two individuals or corporations. Among the dozens of provisions are those to:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Wipe out a 1987 requirement that farmers, construction companies and other tax-exempt off-road users of diesel fuel pay the federal tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and later apply for a refund Farmers especially have objected to the loss of cash flow and paperwork. _ Permanently permit owners of mutual fund shares to deduct certain operating expenses of the fund without regard to a general provision allowing deduction of only miscellaneous expenses that exceed 2 percent of income _ Allow a worker to avoid tax on up to $ 1,500 of year of employer-provided education assistance, down from an earlier $ 5,250 level Most graduate education -LRB- except for teaching or research assistance -RRB- would not qualify. _ Extend through 1990 a tax credit for owners of newly constructed low-income rental housing _ Impose a tax of $ 2.67 per pound on pipe tobacco _ Extend through 1990 a tax exemption for bonds issued by state and local governments to help low-income families buy their first home _ Allow free-lance writers, artists and photographers to deduct work-related expenses even before a project produces income Similar relief from general `` uniform capitalization'' rules would be included for certain livestock producers -LRB- the so-called heifer tax -RRB- and growers of pistachio nuts. _ Allow an 80 percent deduction for contributions to college athletic scholarship funds even when such `` gifts'' guarantee a fan the privilege of buying a game ticket _ Extend through 1990 a credit under which the government pays the first year of wages for certain newly hired economically disadvantaged workers _ Repeal the completed-contract accounting method, which has produced tax savings for defense contractors and large construction companies _ Reduce from 70 percent to 50 percent the dividend-received deduction for corporations that own less than 20 percent of the stock in another _ Repeal a provision that has allowed <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Native </ORGANIZATION> corporations to sell some of their unused tax credits to other companies Lawmakers say the benefit has been badly abused. _ Remove some of the tax advantages of using single-premium life insurance as an investment Loans from such policies would be taxed as cash withdrawals; the new rules would apply to policies whose cash value builds more quickly than one paid through seven equal annual premiums. _ Allow rural mail carriers to deduct 33.75 cents for each mile a personal car is driven on a mail route; most people are allowed 22.5 cents a mile for business-related mileage _ Permit operators of offshore or <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil rigs and of some commercial vessels -LRB- but not luxury liners -RRB- to deduct the full cost of meals provided to employees; most business may deduct only 80 percent _ Allow a surviving spouse to defer taxation on certain profits from the sale of a principal home, just as though the spouse had not died Present law denies such a break if a spouse dies after a home is sold and before a new one is built. _ Prohibit any person with a home-based business -LRB- including moonlighters -RRB- from deducting any part of the base monthly telephone charge as a business expense _ Deny Social Security benefits to deported Nazi war criminals _ Permit states and blood-collection facilities to require blood donors to list their Social Security numbers so they can be traced if tests determine their blood is carryng the AIDS virus _ Exempt from <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> taxes employees from <LOCATION> Amish </LOCATION> and other sects with religious objections to the program; self-employed already are exempt
