<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     08-05 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Checkmates,' A New Comedy, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Checkmates'' is a crudely constructed, cartoonish comedy by <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Milner </PERSON> about the generation gap, but this time the gap is n't between father and son or mother and daughter. It's a chasm between two married couples. These middle-class couples also happen to be black, but do n't expect any revelations about race relations and what being black in a white society can do to a marriage `` Checkmates,'' which opened Thursday at the 46th Street Theater, is played mainly for laughs _ cheap laughs, easy laughs, laughs that do little to illuminate character or advance the plot. Plot is something that `` Checkmates'' rarely encounters. The play is mostly a series of sitcom sketches populated by one couple or the other as they fight, make love or just try to get through the day. Naturally, these people are a study in contrast. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mattie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> have been married for 45 years. They have four children, six grandchildren and a comfortable home in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> where they are getting through <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s retirement by talking about the couple upstairs. Their tenants are <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> and <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, young, upwardly mobile and and preoccupied with `` self'' rather than `` we.'' He's a salesman. She works as a buyer for a department store. Career conflicts _ she's on the way up, he could be on the way down _ threaten their marriage. The audience watches as one marriage reaffirms itself and the other falls apart. But it's hard to care for these characters whether they are up or down. <PERSON> Milner </PERSON> wrote the book for `` Do n't Get God Started,'' a gospel show that ran on Broadway for several months last season. It was a musical morality tale with dramatized lessons about life and love interspersed with some rousing gospel songs. Those same messages about sharing, caring and giving show up in `` Checkmates,'' but this time there are no soaring melodies to lift the spirits between the sagging and soggy vingettes. To pad out the evening, the playwright flashes back to tell the older couple's story. You can tell when that happens because the lighting _ some lurid effects by designer <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> _ changes color. In these moments, the audience learns of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s decision to leave his family and fight during World War II as well as his affair with a French woman. At least the production has been superbly cast, with <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> starring as the older duo and <PERSON> Denzel </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marsha </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> appearing as the younger couple. Miss <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> is a radiant actress and <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> a forceful stage presence, so they mine the comedy for every giggle they can. It's depressing to watch them work so hard with such meager results <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has an ingratiating stage manner. He survives because of his winning personality and not because of anything the author gives him to say or do. Miss <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, as the young wife, has a harder job. She must always be on the offensive, hammering away at her husband or whining about her job, and the complaints grow tiresome. The wide stage at the 46th Street Theater has been sliced in half by two separate apartments, both realistically designed by <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Burbridge </PERSON>. The action alternates between the two homes with the predictability of a boring tennis match. Director <PERSON> Woodie </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, Jr., does n't do anything to lessen the ping-pong effect. But it's hard to see what King could have done to liven up the evening. Because of <PERSON> Milner </PERSON>'s simple-minded and obvious script, `` Checkmates'' is checkmated even before the curtain goes up.
</TEXT>
