<FIRST>r f PM-EconomyRdp     08-05 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Productivity Deteriorates In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with Labor Department report on July
unemployment, scheduled for 8:30 am EDT release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Business productivity deteriorated at a rate not seen in seven years while labor costs soared during the second quarter, the government has said in a report that sparked sparking concern over the future of the economy's competitive vigor. In another report on Thursday, the nation's largest retailers said sales for July were lackluster as unusually hot weather kept many consumers out of stores. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> said the efficiency of non-farm businesses in producing goods and services declined 1.7 percent in the quarter ended June 30, its first decline in two years and the biggest drop since 1981. Productivity had risen at an annual rate of 3.4 percent in the second quarter and had been improving at a rate of 1 percent to 2 percent annually in the previous three years. Reflecting the strong economic expansion, output of goods and services by those businesses responsible for three-fourths of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic activity rose 4.7 percent in the second quarter. But to achieve that growth, companies increased their work hours by 6.5 percent, hiring hundreds of thousands of new employees to send the unemployment rate to a 14-year low of 5.3 percent. Meanwhile, labor costs soared 5.9 percent in the first quarter as hourly wages and benefits rose at an annual rate of 4.1 percent. After taking into account a 4.4 percent annual rate of inflation in the last 18 months, workers' purchasing power actually declined 0.6 percent from April through June, the department said. Among retailers, the nation's biggest store chains were at the mercy of weather extremes as a relentless heat wave kept shoppers home last month, preventing stores from clearing out their summer merchandise. The July results ended a modest recovery the stores enjoyed in June, which had followed a slump in April and May caused by cold and rain. Overall, consumers have cut back on their retail outlays over the past year and a half because of high installment debt levels and uncertainty about the economy. As a result, retailers' sales have been a soft spot in an otherwise strong economy. Consumer spending, which also includes expenditures for food, medical care, autos, utilities, transportation and other necessities, is watched closely because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product.
</TEXT>
