<TEXT>
 Hot weather sent the nation's largest general retailers back into a slump during July, but the stores and Wall Street analysts are looking toward August with some optimism. Last month's relentless heat largely kept shoppers out of stores, hampered retailers' attempts to clear out summer merchandise and made sales reports issued by the stores Thursday disappointing. The higher temperatures ended a modest rally the retailers enjoyed in June. In addition to weather, the stores' reports reflected the overall softness that has plagued the retail industry for about a year and a half, said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Feiner </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Consumers have cut back on their retail spending because of high installment debt levels and uncertainty about the economy As a result, retailers' sales have been a soft spot in an otherwise strong economy. Consumer spending, which also includes expenditures for food, medical care, autos, utilities, transportation and other necessities, is watched closely because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said July generally is not an important month for retailers. But this month will be critical, especially for apparel retailers who have been in a year-long slump as women turned away from the retailers' offerings of shorter skirts and clothes shoppers widely perceived as boring. The retailers have revamped their fall lines, and analysts predict there will be a pickup in clothing sales that may begin showing up in the stores' August results. `` I would expect sales would accelerate,'' <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON> said. `` I am looking for a good August.'' In their reports Thursday, several retailers recorded sales increases under 3 percent _ meaning the stores were losing ground to inflation, which has run at an annual rate of 4.4 percent so far this year. The nation's largest retailer, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said its overall sales rose 7.2 percent last month and 5.4 percent for the first half of the fiscal year, compared with the same periods of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' sales for stores open at least a year, so-called same-store sales, were up 2.5 percent last month and 2.1 percent for the year so far. Retailers and industry analysts believe same-store sales are a more accurate yardstick of a company's performance than figures which include sales from new stores. K mart <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 4.8 percent last month and 5.3 percent during the first half, while same-store sales edged up 0.7 percent in July and 1.8 percent for the year to date. <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 30 percent in July and 31 percent for the first half. Same-store sales rose 14 percent last month and 12 percent so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 2.7 percent in July and 2.6 percent for the first six months Same-store sales were up 2.1 percent last month and 1.6 percent in the first half. <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales were up 13.1 percent last month, and 17.6 percent for the year to date. The company's same-store sales slipped 0.9 percent during July, while rising 1.5 percent over the first half May <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 23.5 percent in July, and 12 percent over the first half. Same-stores sales increased 4 percent for the month, and 1.2 percent so far this year. F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported an 11.1 percent sales gain for July, and an 11.9 increase for the first six months. <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 1 percent last month, and 2.8 percent over the first half. The results reported Thursday were from general merchandise and apparel retailers. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by the federal government, they do not include sales at auto dealers, supermarkets or restaurants.
