<FIRST>r f PM-BizWeekProbe     08-05 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Biz Week Probe,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Week Tells Its Side Of Scandal Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business Week says it has not uncovered any evidence implicating its editorial employees in a spreading scandal involving pre-publication leaks of the magazine's stock tips, and again has defended its actions in dealing internally with its suspicions without telling authorities. The magazine in its Aug. 15 issue, released to the press late Thursday, gave its first detailed account of the scandal, two weeks after first confirming it was investigating the leaks. So far, seven people around the nation have been forced from their jobs in connection with the magazine scandal, and federal law enforcement officials have begun a criminal investigation. Evidence uncovered so far suggests some printers at two of the four plants that print Business Week peddled unpublished copies to brokers, who bought stocks recommended by the `` Inside Wall Street'' column and sold them later at a profit after publication attracted more buyers and boosted the price of the stocks. In the Aug. 15 issue, Business Week estimated that price changes in 20 stocks mentioned in the column this year generated potential profits of $ 2.4 million. `` Few appear to have made a killing,'' the magazine said. Business Week, which is published by <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said its editors detected questionable price changes in stocks mentioned in the column as far back as early last year. But the magazine's editors met with <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, who recommended against reporting the matter to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, Business Week said. The story said Business Week had nothing but suspicions about stock price movements and had no concrete evidence implicating anyone. While Business Week was under no legal obligation to notify the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, the story said, magazine editors also were concerned that an investigation `` might raise First Amendment problems,'' namely that investigators might demand the names of confidential sources of <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcial </PERSON>, who regularly writes the column. Instead, the magazine attempted to `` police its own shop'' by sharply reducing the number of Business Week copies distributed in the <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> building before the official release date from 600 to 20. The magazine also sent letters to its printers citing `` the widespread concern about insider trading'' and reminding them of the confidentiality policy. Business Week said the suspicious trading seemed to subside for awhile, but then reappeared this past spring. The price moves attracted the attention of the Stock Watch department of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which began its own inquiry but did not notify Business Week or the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, the story said. The Dow Jones Professional Investor Report made the first public disclosure of the suspicious stock movements in a story July 21, Business Week finally confirmed its own probe and the scandal began snowballing.
</TEXT>
