<FIRST>r f PM-Ethics-Education Bjt   08-05 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethics-Education, Bjt,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accounting Firm Helping Business Schools Expand Ethics Education</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the world's biggest accounting firms is spearheading a $ 5 million program to help smaller colleges and universities improve their teaching of business ethics, prompted by a survey indicating that ethics programs were `` a little spotty.'' Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has developed PACE, a five-year program of seminars aimed at helping faculty at business schools nationwide to make ethics instruction part of their basic course work. <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kullberg </PERSON>, the firm's managing partner and chief executive officer, said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> views the program partly as an investment in its own future. `` As one of the nation's largest employers of business school graduates, we have a significant interest in their development,'' <PERSON> Kullberg </PERSON> said. `` This program benefits <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> as well as the business community in general.'' Wall Street's insider-trading scandals and shady defense-contract deals have focused public attention on moral issues in business. But while many graduate business schools have responded by introducing ethics courses _ often as electives for MBA candidates _ few small colleges and public universities can match the resources of the leading private business schools in developing such programs. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, for example, received a $ 30 million gift last year from former <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S.R </PERSON>. Shad to finance a program in ethics education. But <PERSON> Kullberg </PERSON> said an Andersen-financed survey found the development of ethics-education in the business curriculums of smaller colleges and public universities to be `` a little spotty.'' `` There is a desire to find a solution, a desire to find a practical way to deal with the subject,'' he said in a telephone interview this week. So <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> developed the PACE program and invited business-school instructors from around the nation to review it. Some 300 of them came to the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area this spring and summer at <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>'s expense to attend two-day seminars on incorporating ethics lessons into their routine course work. <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> has asked the approximately 60 institutions that sent representatives to this year's seminars to try the PACE approach for at least one semester. The team of ethics teachers, business school instructors and business professionals who developed PACE decided ethics should be taught as part of the five basic business disciplines: finance, marketing, economics, management and accounting. `` I see that as a big plus,'' said <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Doenges </PERSON>, a professor of finance at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> who attended a PACE seminar. In real life, <PERSON> Doenges </PERSON> said, `` ethical issues can arise at any point at almost any time.'' By incorporating ethics discussions into finance courses, he said, `` the student sees ethical issues as a part of finance, as a part of his normal business life rather than as a segmented or compartmented area of study.'' To foster discussions, PACE offers fictitious case studies tailored to each discipline. The case studies are meant to reflect ethical dilemmas that business students might face early in their careers, such as sexual harassment, truth in advertising, plant closings, wage discrimination and ledger manipulation. The dilemmas have no easy or correct solutions, but are designed to get students talking and thinking. `` Students need to grapple with these issues so they can have some experience in thinking about these issues,'' said <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>, an assistant professor of accounting at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fuqua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> DePaul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and a member of the PACE development group, said the PACE program was designed to give business students the basic skill to deal with ethical dilemmas, just as they learned the basic skills of management and accounting. `` We believe very strongly that most ethical problems that arise come from lack of information and that lack of information results in poor judgment,'' he said. `` We're trying to provide the information that will help alleviate those bad judgments.''
</TEXT>
