<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday charged <ORGANIZATION> Towers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which has made takeover overtures for <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, with selling $ 20 million in unregistered securities. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filed a civil suit alleging that Towers failed to satisfy disclosure requirements when it publicly sold $ 20 million in notes between October 1986 and October 1987. Towers is a factoring firm, which buys accounts receivable at a discount and earns a profit by collecting the full face amount. `` We say they financed a factoring program with an unlawful securities offering and we want them to stop,'' said <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Gettinger </PERSON>, a staff attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to bar Towers from using the money it received in the securities sales and to issue an injunction barring the company from further violation of federal registration requirements. The agency also said it wanted Towers to return the noteholders' money. <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorkin </PERSON>, who represents <ORGANIZATION> Towers </ORGANIZATION>, said the company and its top executives recognized that `` there may be a technical violation of the registration provisions of the Federal securities laws and will make every effort to comply with those provisions.'' Towers, beginning last year, made a number of announcements indicating it might make a bid for <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, but has yet to mount a takeover and was regarded by Wall Street as a questionable suitor. But its overtures attracted public attention because the firm said its offer included support from former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>.
