<HEAD>LTV Corp. Earnings Up 28 Percent In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, operating under Chapter 11 protection from creditors, said Thursday its second quarter net income rose by 28.4 percent over the same period last year. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> said its net income in the three months ended June 30 rose to $ 157.6 million, or $ 1.14 per share, from $ 122.7 million, or 91 cents per share, a year earlier. A strong increase in steel sales boosted <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue to $ 2.1 billion, up from $ 1.9 billion a year earlier. For the six months ended June 30, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> had net income of $ 321.5 million, or $ 2.67 per share, compared with net income of $ 252.3 million, or $ 2.17 per share, for the first six months of 1987. Revenue for the six months to $ 3.94 billion from $ 3.84 billion. `` The domestic steel industry's performance has improved as a result of massive cost cutting, cyclical factors and a more reasonably valued dollar,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive. `` However, the industry continues to face the threats of unfairly priced imported steel, and inadequate long-term return on invested capital, as well as the risks of successfully weathering the next economic downturn.'' Hay emphasized a need to extend voluntary restraint agreements, set to expire in 1898, to limit steel imports. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> in May submitted a reorganization plan to creditor groups for consideration. At the end of the second quarter, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> had a negative net worth of $ 1.7 billion.
